AGI - The Court of Appeal of <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-03-24/hong-kong-new-law-security-national-25808040/">Hong Kong</a> banned the pro-democracy song "Glory to Hong Kong>", diffused during the protests of 2019 in the special administrative region.&nsp; The authorities said that the track – linked to protests and disorders 5 years ago – was “erroneously and repeatedly presented” as the hymn of the city. They refer to those cases, often international sporting events, in which by confusion he was played instead of the Chinese anthem. It is estimated, in all situations, that this happened at least 800 times.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Last July, the High Court dismissed the government's proposal, stating that the move could have a "greater effect" on freedom of speech. But the authorities challenged the decision of the court, now overturned.&nbsp;During the appeal, a lawyer representing the city government had cited an interview issued by the song composer, in which&nbsp; the latter was called "a weapon" that contributed to the development of protests.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Composed with the help of multiple protesters, and with written parts also thanks to the suggestions of users of the LIHKG online forum, the song was released on YouTube in August 2019. Includes the slogan "liberate Hong Kong, revolution of our times»", a common refrain sung by the crowd during the riots. Since then the slogan has been &nbsp; judged by the authorities capable of inciting secession, a crime under Beijing's national security law, which can punish offenders with life imprisonment.
&nbsp;
Immediately the reaction of Beijing that defined the measure "necessary". "To teach anyone to use or spread the song in question is a legitimate and necessary measure by Hong Kong to fulfill their responsibility to safeguard national security," said foreign ministry spokesman Lin Jian in a briefing.
&nbsp;

